WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-US

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:06.000
JUDY WOODRUFF: Good evening.

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:07.000
I'm Judy Woodruff.

00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:08.880
On the "NewsHour" tonight: The war continues.

00:00:08.880 --> 00:00:15.480
As Ukrainian forces hold off Russian advances
in the east, a massive effort by Western allies

00:00:15.480 --> 00:00:16.880
to arm Ukraine.

00:00:16.880 --> 00:00:23.850
Then, 30 years later, Los Angeles reflects
on the uprising that followed the brutal police

00:00:23.850 --> 00:00:26.859
beating of Rodney King and its impact on policing.

00:00:26.859 --> 00:00:32.800
DARNELL HUNT, Dean of Social Services, UCLA:
All the basic measures of economic well-being

00:00:32.800 --> 00:00:36.379
across the different racial and ethnic groups,
there's been very, very little progress since

00:00:36.379 --> 00:00:37.379
1992.

00:00:37.379 --> 00:00:38.379
And, in some cases, we have gone backwards.

00:00:38.379 --> 00:00:41.110
JUDY WOODRUFF: And it's Friday.

00:00:41.110 --> 00:00:46.079
David Brooks and Jonathan Capehart weigh in
on new polling that shows Democrats losing

00:00:46.079 --> 00:00:51.190
ground to Republicans as the parties gear
up for midterm elections.

00:00:51.190 --> 00:00:53.143
All that and more on tonight's "PBS NewsHour."

00:00:53.143 --> 00:02:41.462
(BREAK)

00:02:41.462 --> 00:02:47.090
JUDY WOODRUFF: Desperate attempts to evacuate
the besieged city of Mariupol continue today,

00:02:47.090 --> 00:02:51.400
with the United Nations trying to strike a
deal with Russian forces that would allow

00:02:51.400 --> 00:02:56.040
more than 100,000 civilians to leave the port
city.

00:02:56.040 --> 00:02:58.660
Fighting raged elsewhere in Ukraine's east.

00:02:58.660 --> 00:03:04.200
And, in the capital of Kyiv, rescuers took
stock of a deadly missile strike that hit

00:03:04.200 --> 00:03:07.650
as the U.N. secretary-general visited last
night.

00:03:07.650 --> 00:03:10.959
Special correspondent Willem Marx reports.

00:03:10.959 --> 00:03:16.500
WILLEM MARX: In Ukraine's east, the roar of
artillery remains relentless.

00:03:16.500 --> 00:03:21.550
Swirls of smoke stain the sky in the city
of Lyman, now a part of the landscape.

00:03:21.550 --> 00:03:25.980
At a nearby hospital, Tatiana receives treatment
for her injuries.

00:03:25.980 --> 00:03:28.390
She says a missile struck her daughters home.

00:03:28.390 --> 00:03:31.860
The two of them survived, but her grandson
did not.

00:03:31.860 --> 00:03:34.560
And she buried him with her own hands.

00:03:34.560 --> 00:03:38.630
TATIANA MATSEGORA, Lyman, Ukraine Resident
(through translator): It's one thing to bury

00:03:38.630 --> 00:03:42.240
a child, but another thing to bury your grandson.

00:03:42.240 --> 00:03:44.790
He was only 14 years old.

00:03:44.790 --> 00:03:47.280
He asked me: "Grandma, will I live?"

00:03:47.280 --> 00:03:49.380
I said that he would live.

00:03:49.380 --> 00:03:50.970
But I betrayed him.

00:03:50.970 --> 00:03:53.980
I will never forgive myself for it.

00:03:53.980 --> 00:04:00.069
WILLEM MARX: To the south, in Mariupol, more
than 100,000 trapped residents unlikely to

00:04:00.069 --> 00:04:02.930
forgive their occupiers' onslaught.

00:04:02.930 --> 00:04:07.130
Ukraine said today it planned fresh evacuations
from the Azovstal steel plant, the city's

00:04:07.130 --> 00:04:09.900
last Ukraine-held redoubt.

00:04:09.900 --> 00:04:14.980
Inside the plant, a Ukrainian commander said
he's now hopeful his troops can survive the

00:04:14.980 --> 00:04:15.980
siege.

00:04:15.980 --> 00:04:19.659
SVIATOSLAV PALAMAR, Deputy Commander, Azov
Regiment (through translator): I really believe

00:04:19.659 --> 00:04:23.990
that all the defenders of Mariupol, the troops
that remained here, the wounded and those

00:04:23.990 --> 00:04:28.000
alive, that we will be able to save the lives
of these heroes.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:31.280
I have hope that we will be able to get as
many guys out of here alive.

00:04:31.280 --> 00:04:37.250
WILLEM MARX: But there are few signs of life
elsewhere in the city, the local history museum

00:04:37.250 --> 00:04:38.880
reduced to rubble.

00:04:38.880 --> 00:04:44.919
It survived the Second World War, but now
stands as a grim reminder of Putin's invasion.

00:04:44.919 --> 00:04:50.220
The U.S. says the Kremlin seeks to surround
Ukrainian forces in the Donbass region, advancing

00:04:50.220 --> 00:04:53.830
north from Mariupol and south from Izyum.

00:04:53.830 --> 00:04:58.180
But one senior U.S. defense official today
said they believe that Russian advance is

00:04:58.180 --> 00:05:00.560
now days behind schedule.

00:05:00.560 --> 00:05:05.050
In Ukraine's capital meanwhile, missiles yesterday
demolished more homes.

00:05:05.050 --> 00:05:08.410
LIUDMYLA, Kyiv Resident (through translator):
They killed so many people.

00:05:08.410 --> 00:05:09.680
It is really difficult.

00:05:09.680 --> 00:05:15.460
WILLEM MARX: Among the remnants, rescue workers
carried out the body of journalist Vira Hyrych.

00:05:15.460 --> 00:05:20.320
She worked for the U.S.-funded broadcaster
Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty.

00:05:20.320 --> 00:05:26.720
In Irpin, just to Kyiv's northwest, drone
video above block after block of devastation,

00:05:26.720 --> 00:05:32.610
once home to 62,000 residents, the former
battlefield now a ghost town after Russian

00:05:32.610 --> 00:05:35.380
forces withdrew in late March.

00:05:35.380 --> 00:05:40.370
Those missiles in Kyiv, Judy, a reminder these
strikes can still happen anywhere any time

00:05:40.370 --> 00:05:41.389
inside Ukraine.

00:05:41.389 --> 00:05:46.750
But as our teams experienced firsthand over
the past couple of days, by far, the heaviest

00:05:46.750 --> 00:05:50.850
firepower is trained on the country's south
and east.

00:05:50.850 --> 00:05:56.220
A couple days ago, two hours' drive southeast
from here in Dnipro, the town we were visiting

00:05:56.220 --> 00:05:59.930
was rocked by dozens of explosions each and
every hour.

00:05:59.930 --> 00:06:05.350
Today, three hours' drive due east of here,
we met a Ukrainian soldier injured in an artillery

00:06:05.350 --> 00:06:10.870
strike who told us it was one of around 100
shells to have darkened the sky over the course

00:06:10.870 --> 00:06:14.370
of the day over his single unit -- Judy.

00:06:14.370 --> 00:06:18.990
JUDY WOODRUFF: Willem Marx in Ukraine, we
thank you.

00:06:18.990 --> 00:06:19.990
And a reminder.

00:06:19.990 --> 00:06:24.450
The "NewsHour"'s coverage of the war in Ukraine
is supported in partnership with the Pulitzer

00:06:24.450 --> 00:06:25.550
Center.

00:06:25.550 --> 00:06:30.590
With the war raging in Eastern Ukraine, there
is a divide between the war aims declared

00:06:30.590 --> 00:06:35.080
by the Russian high command in Moscow and
the reality of the war on the ground.

00:06:35.080 --> 00:06:36.580
Amna Nawaz has that.

00:06:36.580 --> 00:06:37.770
AMNA NAWAZ: That's right, Judy.

00:06:37.770 --> 00:06:41.990
For more on the state of the war in Ukraine,
we turn once again to Dmitri Alperovitch.

00:06:41.990 --> 00:06:45.289
he's co-founder of the Silverado Policy Accelerator.

00:06:45.289 --> 00:06:46.710
That's a Washington-based think tank.

00:06:46.710 --> 00:06:48.449
Dmitri, welcome back to the "NewsHour."

00:06:48.449 --> 00:06:49.449
Thanks for joining us.

00:06:49.449 --> 00:06:53.100
Let's start with your assessment of that Russian
war effort on the ground.

00:06:53.100 --> 00:06:55.849
I spoke earlier with the Pentagon spokesman,
John Kirby.

00:06:55.849 --> 00:07:00.630
He said, yes, Russia is learning from earlier
missteps, they are better at resupplying forces

00:07:00.630 --> 00:07:04.870
in the field, better at combining their air
and ground capabilities, but their progress

00:07:04.870 --> 00:07:06.900
has been slow and uneven.

00:07:06.900 --> 00:07:08.550
What's your read on how they're doing?

00:07:08.550 --> 00:07:11.590
DMITRI ALPEROVITCH, Co-Founder, Silverado
Policy Accelerator: That's absolutely right.

00:07:11.590 --> 00:07:15.479
The reality is that the Russians have learned
from their mistakes, and they're using overwhelming

00:07:15.479 --> 00:07:19.919
fires, as we have just heard from the report,
shelling indiscriminately the Ukrainian positions,

00:07:19.919 --> 00:07:23.740
killing, of course, many civilians in the
process, but they're still making very little

00:07:23.740 --> 00:07:27.020
progress because they're up against very well-armed
Ukrainians now.

00:07:27.020 --> 00:07:28.700
They're getting supplies from the West.

00:07:28.700 --> 00:07:30.960
They're entrenched in their defensive positions.

00:07:30.960 --> 00:07:33.150
And that's making it very, very difficult
for the Russians.

00:07:33.150 --> 00:07:34.360
And they're taking heavy casualties.

00:07:34.360 --> 00:07:39.229
AMNA NAWAZ: Admiral Kirby also mentioned specifically
the role of conscripts in this case, that

00:07:39.229 --> 00:07:43.290
they're sort of being inundated with propaganda
back home about how well the effort is going,

00:07:43.290 --> 00:07:45.759
and then they get there on the ground and
find a very different situation.

00:07:45.759 --> 00:07:48.870
He says that's contributing to Russia's lack
of success.

00:07:48.870 --> 00:07:50.360
Have you seen that as well?

00:07:50.360 --> 00:07:51.360
DMITRI ALPEROVITCH: Absolutely.

00:07:51.360 --> 00:07:52.430
The morale is very low.

00:07:52.430 --> 00:07:57.599
The majority of the fighting force is still
professionals who are getting paid, contractors

00:07:57.599 --> 00:07:58.599
in the Russian military.

00:07:58.599 --> 00:08:01.370
But we have seen, of course, conscripts being
put into this fight.

00:08:01.370 --> 00:08:05.379
And the difference sometimes is really in
the name, because a lot of these conscripts

00:08:05.379 --> 00:08:10.139
are sort of forced into signing contracts
once they're trying to get out.

00:08:10.139 --> 00:08:13.580
And we're seeing that no one really wants
to fight in Ukraine.

00:08:13.580 --> 00:08:15.740
And they're making very little progress as
a result.

00:08:15.740 --> 00:08:18.070
AMNA NAWAZ: Dmitri, what about the Ukrainian
response?

00:08:18.070 --> 00:08:22.440
As you just heard reported there, they are
getting supplies of more and heavier weaponry

00:08:22.440 --> 00:08:23.849
from the U.S. and NATO.

00:08:23.849 --> 00:08:27.060
Admiral Kirby said, look, they get it in,
and then the Ukrainians have to figure out

00:08:27.060 --> 00:08:29.360
how to move it wherever it needs to go.

00:08:29.360 --> 00:08:33.000
Are they able to get that weaponry to the
places they need it?

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:35.289
DMITRI ALPEROVITCH: The logistics are very
challenging.

00:08:35.289 --> 00:08:36.599
They're relying on rail.

00:08:36.599 --> 00:08:39.180
And the Russians this week have started to
target rail infrastructure.

00:08:39.180 --> 00:08:43.870
They targeted a number of substations in Western
Ukraine to try to shut down rail.

00:08:43.870 --> 00:08:48.431
They have only been temporarily successful,
caused about two hours of outage in some of

00:08:48.431 --> 00:08:49.431
these locations.

00:08:49.431 --> 00:08:51.610
So the Ukrainians are still able to resupply.

00:08:51.610 --> 00:08:55.950
And that is why you're seeing the Russians
make such a big push in the Donbass so quickly,

00:08:55.950 --> 00:08:59.930
before they have been able to really send
all their reinforcements into this fight,

00:08:59.930 --> 00:09:01.890
which the doctrine would dictate they should.

00:09:01.890 --> 00:09:05.310
And, as a result, they're rushing because
they really want to cut off those supplies

00:09:05.310 --> 00:09:07.570
from coming into the Donbass region.

00:09:07.570 --> 00:09:10.830
AMNA NAWAZ: Tell me a little bit more about
what's at stake in the Donbass and, of course,

00:09:10.830 --> 00:09:14.529
the Mariupol target that they're still trying
to capture there, which would give them a

00:09:14.529 --> 00:09:17.750
crucial land bridge connecting those territories
they control.

00:09:17.750 --> 00:09:20.580
What's at stake there, beyond just the military
play?

00:09:20.580 --> 00:09:23.580
DMITRI ALPEROVITCH: Well, at this point, it's
prestige.

00:09:23.580 --> 00:09:27.800
It's the ability to say that we have won this
fight, even though the initial objectives,

00:09:27.800 --> 00:09:31.510
of course, of taking Kyiv, changing the government
have not panned out.

00:09:31.510 --> 00:09:34.730
But they're trying to say that, never mind,
we didn't want to do that anyway.

00:09:34.730 --> 00:09:37.470
This was all about protecting the Russian
population in the Donbass.

00:09:37.470 --> 00:09:41.790
And if they can claim that they have been
able to take what were the old boundaries

00:09:41.790 --> 00:09:45.860
of Donetsk and Luhansk, at least two statelets
that they have created, if they can say that

00:09:45.860 --> 00:09:50.810
they now have the land corridor to Crimea,
they can proclaim victory politically.

00:09:50.810 --> 00:09:51.810
President Putin can.

00:09:51.810 --> 00:09:53.960
But here's the reality for the Ukrainians.

00:09:53.960 --> 00:09:58.260
Even if they manage to hold the Donbass and
prevent the Russians from capturing much of

00:09:58.260 --> 00:10:03.709
that territory, the remaining territory, they
still face a very tough situation economically.

00:10:03.709 --> 00:10:06.120
The Black Sea is blockaded by the Russians.

00:10:06.120 --> 00:10:09.980
That means all the ports that the Ukrainians
have both in the Azov Sea and in the Black

00:10:09.980 --> 00:10:11.870
Sea are not functioning.

00:10:11.870 --> 00:10:14.630
And that was the majority of their exports,
the vast majority.

00:10:14.630 --> 00:10:18.660
Over 135 million tons a year would go through
those ports.

00:10:18.660 --> 00:10:25.070
Now they're hoping to get about a million
tons a month through the rail infrastructure

00:10:25.070 --> 00:10:29.530
down into Poland and Romania, just about a
10th of what they actually need.

00:10:29.530 --> 00:10:30.910
And that's 40 percent of their GDP.

00:10:30.910 --> 00:10:34.709
So the Ukrainian economy is really being starved
to death right now by the Russians.

00:10:34.709 --> 00:10:38.630
AMNA NAWAZ: And, Dmitri, in just the 30 seconds
or so we have left, do you even know what

00:10:38.630 --> 00:10:41.300
victory looks like for Ukrainians at this
point?

00:10:41.300 --> 00:10:44.970
DMITRI ALPEROVITCH: Well, obviously, they
have been able to preserve their government,

00:10:44.970 --> 00:10:47.740
preserve their freedom, but can they preserve
their economy?

00:10:47.740 --> 00:10:50.030
That is the question right now.

00:10:50.030 --> 00:10:53.820
They require about $5 billion to $7 billion
in aid a month right now.

00:10:53.820 --> 00:10:56.260
The West, of course, is supporting them, but
how long can they go?

00:10:56.260 --> 00:10:57.260
Can they go for years?

00:10:57.260 --> 00:10:58.500
Can they go for decades?

00:10:58.500 --> 00:11:03.680
They need to get that back -- economy back
up and running, their exports back through

00:11:03.680 --> 00:11:05.100
the maritime ports.

00:11:05.100 --> 00:11:08.860
And if we can't block -- if we can't an break
the blockade that the Russians are instituting

00:11:08.860 --> 00:11:10.720
in the Black Sea, it will be very, very tough
to do.

00:11:10.720 --> 00:11:15.100
AMNA NAWAZ: That is Dmitri Alperovitch of
the Silverado Policy Accelerator joining us

00:11:15.100 --> 00:11:16.100
tonight.

00:11:16.100 --> 00:11:17.100
Dmitri, thanks for your time.

00:11:17.100 --> 00:11:19.750
DMITRI ALPEROVITCH: Thank you.

00:11:19.750 --> 00:11:32.839
JUDY WOODRUFF: In the day's other news: A
Wall Street rout ended a month marked by its

00:11:32.839 --> 00:11:35.540
worst losses in decades.

00:11:35.540 --> 00:11:38.830
Worries over inflation and interest rates
drove the sell-off.

00:11:38.830 --> 00:11:43.339
The Dow Jones industrial average lost 939
points.

00:11:43.339 --> 00:11:45.880
The Nasdaq fell 537.

00:11:45.880 --> 00:11:49.670
The S&amp;P 500 gave up 155.

00:11:49.670 --> 00:11:53.360
All told, the S&amp;P lost nearly 9 percent in
April.

00:11:53.360 --> 00:12:00.670
It's down 13 percent since January, its worst
start to a year since 1939.

00:12:00.670 --> 00:12:03.340
The Nasdaq fell 13 percent this month.

00:12:03.340 --> 00:12:05.610
That's the most since 2008.

00:12:05.610 --> 00:12:08.170
And the Dow lost nearly 5 percent.

00:12:08.170 --> 00:12:14.330
A closely watched gauge of inflation underscored
today what U.S. consumers see for themselves.

00:12:14.330 --> 00:12:19.209
The Commerce Department reported that prices
jumped 6.6 percent in March compared with

00:12:19.209 --> 00:12:20.430
a year ago.

00:12:20.430 --> 00:12:25.209
As with other recent inflation measures, that's
the highest in 40 years.

00:12:25.209 --> 00:12:30.830
Consumer spending rose just over 1 percent,
due mostly to higher prices.

00:12:30.830 --> 00:12:36.260
In China, President Xi Jinping and the Communist
Party's ruling Politburo have reaffirmed a

00:12:36.260 --> 00:12:38.610
zero-COVID strategy.

00:12:38.610 --> 00:12:43.040
The statement today came amid growing outbreaks
in Beijing and Shanghai.

00:12:43.040 --> 00:12:45.990
But officials said the policy is preventing
needless deaths.

00:12:45.990 --> 00:12:49.810
LI BIN, Vice Minister, Chinese National Health
Commission (through translator): China is

00:12:49.810 --> 00:12:54.380
a country with uneven regional development
and insufficient medical resources.

00:12:54.380 --> 00:12:58.860
If the COVID-19 response loosens to let the
virus run free, it will definitely lead to

00:12:58.860 --> 00:13:04.230
a huge number of infections in a short period
of time and a large number of severe and mortal

00:13:04.230 --> 00:13:05.360
cases.

00:13:05.360 --> 00:13:07.360
Medical resources will risk being depleted.

00:13:07.360 --> 00:13:12.500
JUDY WOODRUFF: Meanwhile, Beijing conducted
a third round of mass testing.

00:13:12.500 --> 00:13:17.360
And food had to be delivered through fences
in one blocked-off neighborhood.

00:13:17.360 --> 00:13:22.800
A powerful bomb exploded at a mosque in Afghanistan's
capital today.

00:13:22.800 --> 00:13:27.320
The leader of the mosque in Kabul said that
at least 50 people were killed.

00:13:27.320 --> 00:13:31.370
The Taliban government put the official death
toll at 10.

00:13:31.370 --> 00:13:36.190
Taliban officials arrived, and ambulances
evacuated dozens of wounded.

00:13:36.190 --> 00:13:39.959
Shaken survivors told of a blast that tore
through worshipers.

00:13:39.959 --> 00:13:45.610
MOHAMMAD BASHIR, Survivor (through translator):
A number of Taliban members were inside the

00:13:45.610 --> 00:13:46.880
mosque too.

00:13:46.880 --> 00:13:51.209
And while we were worshiping and standing
to finish our service, the explosion erupted.

00:13:51.209 --> 00:13:54.050
And I was covered with small pieces of victims'
body parts.

00:13:54.050 --> 00:13:58.680
JUDY WOODRUFF: This was the latest in a series
of mosque attacks, many of them claimed by

00:13:58.680 --> 00:14:00.959
the Islamic State group.

00:14:00.959 --> 00:14:05.570
In Israel, there's been more violence at Jerusalem's
Al-Aqsa Mosque compound.

00:14:05.570 --> 00:14:10.820
Early today, Palestinian youths started throwing
stones inside the complex.

00:14:10.820 --> 00:14:14.399
Israeli police then moved in, firing rubber
bullets.

00:14:14.399 --> 00:14:17.490
Palestinian medics said that dozens were wounded.

00:14:17.490 --> 00:14:24.070
By midday, calm returned, and Friday prayers
were peaceful, as tens of thousands of Muslims

00:14:24.070 --> 00:14:27.620
marked the last Friday of Ramadan.

00:14:27.620 --> 00:14:34.570
Back in this country, a federal court in Virginia
sentenced Islamic State member Alexanda Kotey

00:14:34.570 --> 00:14:42.180
to life in prison in the murders of four Americans
in Syria in 2014 and 2015.

00:14:42.180 --> 00:14:46.380
Kotey's terror cell was known as the Beatles
for their British accents.

00:14:46.380 --> 00:14:52.709
Their victims included journalists James Foley
and Steven Sotloff and aid workers Kayla Mueller

00:14:52.709 --> 00:14:54.490
and Peter Kassig.

00:14:54.490 --> 00:14:57.910
Three of the four were beheaded.

00:14:57.910 --> 00:15:03.010
Major League Baseball suspended Los Angeles
Dodgers pitcher Trevor Bauer today for two

00:15:03.010 --> 00:15:04.360
seasons.

00:15:04.360 --> 00:15:08.420
A San Diego woman alleges that Bauer beat
and sexually abused her.

00:15:08.420 --> 00:15:09.420
He denies it.

00:15:09.420 --> 00:15:14.029
And Los Angeles prosecutors have said there's
not enough evidence to pursue charges.

00:15:14.029 --> 00:15:16.510
Bauer said he will appeal the suspension.

00:15:16.510 --> 00:15:22.670
And, in London, former tennis great Boris
Becker was sentenced to 2.5 years in prison

00:15:22.670 --> 00:15:24.630
for hiding personal wealth.

00:15:24.630 --> 00:15:27.350
The 54-year-old German declared bankruptcy
in 2017.

00:15:27.350 --> 00:15:34.579
Later, a British court found that he illicitly
transferred hundreds of thousands of dollars

00:15:34.579 --> 00:15:35.699
in assets.

00:15:35.699 --> 00:15:40.160
Still to come on the "NewsHour": new polling
data suggests a struggle for Democrats in

00:15:40.160 --> 00:15:44.990
the upcoming midterm elections; David Brooks
and Jonathan Capehart break down the week's

00:15:44.990 --> 00:15:50.860
political headlines; a new novel imagines
a world in which our memories can be accessed

00:15:50.860 --> 00:16:02.759
and reviewed by ourselves and by others; plus
much more.

00:16:02.759 --> 00:16:14.380
Anti-Semitic incidents hit a record high last
year in the United States.

00:16:14.380 --> 00:16:17.750
William Brangham has more on what is behind
the rise in hate.

00:16:17.750 --> 00:16:22.300
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Judy, the Anti-Defamation
League, which tracks anti-Semitic behavior

00:16:22.300 --> 00:16:28.199
nationwide, found 2,717 incidents in 2021.

00:16:28.199 --> 00:16:31.820
That's a 34 percent increase from the year
before.

00:16:31.820 --> 00:16:36.660
That averages to more than seven anti-Semitic
incidents per day.

00:16:36.660 --> 00:16:42.020
Jonathan Greenblatt is the CEO of the Anti-Defamation
League and author of the recent book "It Could

00:16:42.020 --> 00:16:48.720
Happen Here: Why America Is Tipping from Hate
to the Unthinkable and How We Can Stop It."

00:16:48.720 --> 00:16:52.000
Jonathan Greenblatt, good to have you back
on the "NewsHour."

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:59.149
This report documents the most anti-Semitic
attacks in the U.S. since the ADL started

00:16:59.149 --> 00:17:01.610
recording these events back in the 1970s.

00:17:01.610 --> 00:17:05.699
Can you help us understand, how should we
interpret what you have found?

00:17:05.699 --> 00:17:07.439
JONATHAN GREENBLATT, CEO and National Director,
Anti-Defamation League: Well, I think the

00:17:07.439 --> 00:17:12.440
data, unfortunately, speaks for itself in
some ways.

00:17:12.440 --> 00:17:17.540
As you pointed out, this is the highest total
we have ever tracked in more than 40 years

00:17:17.540 --> 00:17:19.459
of doing this work.

00:17:19.459 --> 00:17:23.799
And we should keep in mind that anti-Semitic
acts were going down in the United States

00:17:23.799 --> 00:17:28.900
for almost 15 years, and then ,in 2016, they
started to move up.

00:17:28.900 --> 00:17:33.800
And we're now at the point where we have nearly
triple the number of incidents today that

00:17:33.800 --> 00:17:35.160
we did in 2015.

00:17:35.160 --> 00:17:42.370
I mean, in the past year alone, assaults increased
167 percent.

00:17:42.370 --> 00:17:49.429
And we saw examples of vandalism on the rise,
harassment on the rise.

00:17:49.429 --> 00:17:53.880
So I think anti-Semitism really isn't just,
I would suggest, a Jewish problem.

00:17:53.880 --> 00:17:55.820
It's an American problem.

00:17:55.820 --> 00:17:58.380
It's typically the canary in the coal mine.

00:17:58.380 --> 00:18:03.780
And so, as things are beginning to unravel
more broadly, the Jewish community is often

00:18:03.780 --> 00:18:07.480
the target of scapegoating and victimized
in that way.

00:18:07.480 --> 00:18:09.480
And that's exactly what's happening here.

00:18:09.480 --> 00:18:15.350
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Your report points out a
timeline coincidence, that a lot of these

00:18:15.350 --> 00:18:22.530
attacks really surged right around the 2021
violence between Israel and Hamas in Gaza.

00:18:22.530 --> 00:18:27.039
And, similarly, as you're mentioning, there
were also a similar number of attacks with

00:18:27.039 --> 00:18:30.400
-- on Arab-Americans and Muslim-Americans.

00:18:30.400 --> 00:18:32.809
Why do you think those events were such a
trigger?

00:18:32.809 --> 00:18:36.110
JONATHAN GREENBLATT: I can't speak to the
number of attacks on Arab-Americans during

00:18:36.110 --> 00:18:37.110
that time.

00:18:37.110 --> 00:18:38.500
I'm not really aware.

00:18:38.500 --> 00:18:40.310
But I can tell you -- or Muslim-Americans.

00:18:40.310 --> 00:18:45.220
But I can tell you specifically that, in the
period of May, during the conflict, we saw

00:18:45.220 --> 00:18:51.090
nearly 150 percent increase of anti-Semitic
acts over the same period of time in 2020.

00:18:51.090 --> 00:18:52.789
Now, I will be honest.

00:18:52.789 --> 00:18:58.280
You often see, with incidents in the Middle
East or conflict, things can be triggered

00:18:58.280 --> 00:18:59.280
here at home.

00:18:59.280 --> 00:19:01.760
But we have never seen a situation like this
before.

00:19:01.760 --> 00:19:07.169
You had Jews being beaten and brutalized in
broad daylight, say, in the middle of Times

00:19:07.169 --> 00:19:12.850
Square or Los Angeles or the Strip in Las
Vegas, where people who were simply identified

00:19:12.850 --> 00:19:17.600
as Jewish came under assault and attack.

00:19:17.600 --> 00:19:19.440
That was new.

00:19:19.440 --> 00:19:25.320
And I think what you're seeing is a kind of
normalization of anti-Semitism and extremism.

00:19:25.320 --> 00:19:32.980
And to put this in some degree of context,
we know, for example, that when we saw elected

00:19:32.980 --> 00:19:40.570
officials and people in positions of authority
after the outbreak of COVID denigrating China,

00:19:40.570 --> 00:19:47.770
attacking its policies, making wild claims
about their intentionality of the regime in

00:19:47.770 --> 00:19:52.250
Beijing to spreading COVID around the world,
we saw attacks on Asian Americans here at

00:19:52.250 --> 00:19:53.250
home.

00:19:53.250 --> 00:19:59.310
By the same token, when you have people make
wild claims about the Jewish state, make unhinged

00:19:59.310 --> 00:20:04.470
accusations, maybe it shouldn't surprise us
that then people attack Jewish Americans here

00:20:04.470 --> 00:20:05.510
at home.

00:20:05.510 --> 00:20:11.010
So I think we need people in positions of
authority to kind of dial down the rhetoric,

00:20:11.010 --> 00:20:14.440
to realize that words have consequences, and
to be a bit more responsible.

00:20:14.440 --> 00:20:18.130
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Addressing hatred in any
one individual is obviously a very difficult

00:20:18.130 --> 00:20:19.150
thing to do.

00:20:19.150 --> 00:20:21.659
You talked about lowering the temperature.

00:20:21.659 --> 00:20:26.230
But are there other things that people of
goodwill, that social media companies, that

00:20:26.230 --> 00:20:30.110
other policymakers could do to reduce this
hatred and bigotry?

00:20:30.110 --> 00:20:32.490
JONATHAN GREENBLATT: Certainly, there are
things that can be done.

00:20:32.490 --> 00:20:37.880
So, number one, I think individuals should
be -- feel empowered to interrupt intolerance

00:20:37.880 --> 00:20:38.880
when it happens.

00:20:38.880 --> 00:20:42.669
Call out hate when you hear it, whether it's
directed at Jewish people or, by the way,

00:20:42.669 --> 00:20:43.669
anyone else.

00:20:43.669 --> 00:20:47.840
And, in our polarized society, we often don't
want to -- we point to the other side.

00:20:47.840 --> 00:20:51.470
But we need to call it out when it happens
among our own, conservatives calling it out

00:20:51.470 --> 00:20:53.669
when conservatives do it, liberals calling
it out when liberals do it.

00:20:53.669 --> 00:20:54.669
That's really important.

00:20:54.669 --> 00:20:57.760
I think the social media companies could play
a huge role.

00:20:57.760 --> 00:21:02.630
Their algorithms don't need to amplify intolerance
and anti-Semitism.

00:21:02.630 --> 00:21:07.039
Just a little bit more discretion by the companies
could dial down the drama dramatically.

00:21:07.039 --> 00:21:13.100
And then, finally, I'd like to see policymakers
bring anti-bias education into classrooms,

00:21:13.100 --> 00:21:14.460
bring communities together.

00:21:14.460 --> 00:21:16.070
There's a lot more that could be done.

00:21:16.070 --> 00:21:19.290
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right, Jonathan Greenblatt
of the Anti-Defamation League, thank you so

00:21:19.290 --> 00:21:21.590
much for being here.

00:21:21.590 --> 00:21:28.549
JONATHAN GREENBLATT: Thank you.

00:21:28.549 --> 00:21:38.660
JUDY WOODRUFF: Thirty years ago today, parts
of Los Angeles erupted in unrest after a jury

00:21:38.660 --> 00:21:44.610
acquitted four white Los Angeles police officers
over the videotaped beating of Rodney King,

00:21:44.610 --> 00:21:46.290
a Black motorist.

00:21:46.290 --> 00:21:51.460
On this anniversary, Stephanie Sy revisits
the fallout from the Rodney King beating and

00:21:51.460 --> 00:21:54.470
examines what has and has not changed.

00:21:54.470 --> 00:22:02.230
STEPHANIE SY: For many longtime Angelenos,
the sights and smells of April 29, 1992, are

00:22:02.230 --> 00:22:04.650
still easily conjured.

00:22:04.650 --> 00:22:08.560
Smoke spread across L.A. as buildings were
set on fire.

00:22:08.560 --> 00:22:14.210
Images of looting filled television screens,
and less visible, the hurt expressed through

00:22:14.210 --> 00:22:15.210
peaceful protest.

00:22:15.210 --> 00:22:17.610
RHONDA MITCHELL, Former 911 Operator: You
hear the verdicts, and you hear the one not

00:22:17.610 --> 00:22:20.150
guilty after another.

00:22:20.150 --> 00:22:21.630
I was angry.

00:22:21.630 --> 00:22:23.020
There's no other way for me to say it.

00:22:23.020 --> 00:22:25.710
I was just furious at the justice system.

00:22:25.710 --> 00:22:28.080
DARNELL HUNT, Dean of Social Services, UCLA:
When people had expected some type of justice,

00:22:28.080 --> 00:22:29.900
when it did not happen, it was like another
blow.

00:22:29.900 --> 00:22:31.720
It was like Black lives don't really matter.

00:22:31.720 --> 00:22:35.260
CONNIE RICE, Civil Rights Attorney: I picked
up the phone, and I told my staff: Go get

00:22:35.260 --> 00:22:37.809
your kids, go home, don't leave your houses.

00:22:37.809 --> 00:22:39.669
The city is going to blow."

00:22:39.669 --> 00:22:44.500
STEPHANIE SY: South Los Angeles, where much
of the unrest unfolded, had been home to the

00:22:44.500 --> 00:22:48.059
city's largest Black population for decades.

00:22:48.059 --> 00:22:52.850
Rhonda Mitchell's family, like many, had settled
in L.A.'s Crenshaw district after leaving

00:22:52.850 --> 00:22:54.890
the South during the Great Migration.

00:22:54.890 --> 00:22:57.419
RHONDA MITCHELL: It was just the place to
be.

00:22:57.419 --> 00:22:58.460
Crenshaw was alive.

00:22:58.460 --> 00:22:59.510
It crackled.

00:22:59.510 --> 00:23:04.789
STEPHANIE SY: But, in many parts of L.A.,
tensions between communities of color and

00:23:04.789 --> 00:23:11.289
the LAPD had been simmering since the last
bout of unrest in 1965.

00:23:11.289 --> 00:23:16.110
Mitchell's father, who lived through the Watts
uprising, worried history was repeating itself

00:23:16.110 --> 00:23:18.390
after the Rodney King verdict came down.

00:23:18.390 --> 00:23:22.200
RHONDA MITCHELL: During the riots, I called
him and I asked him how he was doing.

00:23:22.200 --> 00:23:25.480
And he was weary.

00:23:25.480 --> 00:23:29.650
He was sad about what was going on in the
neighborhood.

00:23:29.650 --> 00:23:34.770
CONNIE RICE: There was a lot of pressure and
a lot of kindling, and it just took one spark.

00:23:34.770 --> 00:23:39.750
STEPHANIE SY: Connie Rice was an attorney
for the NAACP's Legal Defense Fund at the

00:23:39.750 --> 00:23:40.750
time.

00:23:40.750 --> 00:23:46.190
CONNIE RICE: African Americans were furious
at LAPD for the humiliation, for the gratuitously

00:23:46.190 --> 00:23:49.720
cruel policing, for the constant harassment.

00:23:49.720 --> 00:23:56.419
STEPHANIE SY: For nearly a week after the
acquittals, long frustrated Angelenos took

00:23:56.419 --> 00:23:57.950
to the streets.

00:23:57.950 --> 00:24:02.250
Nearly 10,000 military troops were deployed
to restore order.

00:24:02.250 --> 00:24:05.490
By the end, more than 50 people were dead.

00:24:05.490 --> 00:24:10.940
Police made over 10,000 arrests, and people
had burned and vandalized $1 billion worth

00:24:10.940 --> 00:24:11.940
of property.

00:24:11.940 --> 00:24:16.470
DARNELL HUNT: It's like Martin Luther King
said a long time ago these types of events

00:24:16.470 --> 00:24:18.179
are the voice of the voiceless.

00:24:18.179 --> 00:24:22.830
STEPHANIE SY: Darnell Hunt is the dean of
social sciences at UCLA.

00:24:22.830 --> 00:24:29.010
In 1992, he was a graduate student and a budding
social scientist observing and documenting

00:24:29.010 --> 00:24:30.010
the events.

00:24:30.010 --> 00:24:32.730
DARNELL HUNT: I had my camcorder, and I was
walking around town trying to get a sense

00:24:32.730 --> 00:24:36.600
of what was happening and how it compared
to what I was seeing on television news.

00:24:36.600 --> 00:24:41.039
And I ran into this old man, who just gestured
me over, and he pointed to a store over here.

00:24:41.039 --> 00:24:42.909
And he said: "See that?

00:24:42.909 --> 00:24:44.409
That's my record store.

00:24:44.409 --> 00:24:50.760
And I would sacrifice that in order to make
sure that our voices are heard."

00:24:50.760 --> 00:24:54.400
STEPHANIE SY: But some people would hear that,
and they would say, but these were their businesses.

00:24:54.400 --> 00:24:55.400
DARNELL HUNT: Yes.

00:24:55.400 --> 00:24:56.870
STEPHANIE SY: This was their community.

00:24:56.870 --> 00:25:00.840
DARNELL HUNT: Well, obviously, for him, he
had lived his whole life as a Black man.

00:25:00.840 --> 00:25:03.049
He had experienced what injustice can be.

00:25:03.049 --> 00:25:04.900
And he was willing to make that sacrifice

00:25:04.900 --> 00:25:09.490
STEPHANIE SY: Media coverage of the time focused
on the looting, the burning and violence,

00:25:09.490 --> 00:25:14.650
without much context for the socioeconomic
disparities and police treatment of people

00:25:14.650 --> 00:25:20.160
of color in Los Angeles that had been fomenting
resentment since the 1960s.

00:25:20.160 --> 00:25:23.720
On that front, progress has been mixed.

00:25:23.720 --> 00:25:29.070
Most news reporters didn't capture the nuance,
says Hunt, who's written books about media

00:25:29.070 --> 00:25:30.070
and race.

00:25:30.070 --> 00:25:35.100
DARNELL HUNT: Overlooking the underlying causes,
the structural causes that -- like inequality,

00:25:35.100 --> 00:25:42.500
racism, racial profiling, economic insecurity,
lack of employment, disinvestment in inner

00:25:42.500 --> 00:25:47.580
cities, all the things that created stress
that led to the explosion that was triggered

00:25:47.580 --> 00:25:49.529
by the Rodney King beating verdicts.

00:25:49.529 --> 00:25:55.520
STEPHANIE SY: Rhonda Mitchell was a 911 operator
for the LAPD at the time and witnessed the

00:25:55.520 --> 00:25:58.870
chaos erupting through the emergency phone
lines.

00:25:58.870 --> 00:26:03.210
RHONDA MITCHELL: We were not answering calls
unless it was really about life and death.

00:26:03.210 --> 00:26:07.690
STEPHANIE SY: She had taken the job for the
pay and security, but, in the aftermath of

00:26:07.690 --> 00:26:10.179
the verdict, her loyalties were divided.

00:26:10.179 --> 00:26:14.750
RHONDA MITCHELL: It was a struggle to work
for the police department and hear what went

00:26:14.750 --> 00:26:20.660
on and know and hear the derogatory remarks
about people of color.

00:26:20.660 --> 00:26:22.880
STEPHANIE SY: You would hear racist comments?

00:26:22.880 --> 00:26:24.200
RHONDA MITCHELL: Yes.

00:26:24.200 --> 00:26:27.320
And that's where it gets a little muddled
for me, because we want the police in our

00:26:27.320 --> 00:26:28.320
community.

00:26:28.320 --> 00:26:29.320
We want our community safe.

00:26:29.320 --> 00:26:31.330
We don't want drug dealers all over the place.

00:26:31.330 --> 00:26:34.440
But the police didn't know how to interact
with us.

00:26:34.440 --> 00:26:38.150
The trust had already been lost there between
us and the police.

00:26:38.150 --> 00:26:44.549
STEPHANIE SY: The problems at the LAPD were
partly addressed with diversity recruitment.

00:26:44.549 --> 00:26:47.830
The force is now majority people of color.

00:26:47.830 --> 00:26:53.730
But police killings of Black and brown Angelenos
are still often in the headlines, and accountability

00:26:53.730 --> 00:26:54.850
is rare.

00:26:54.850 --> 00:27:00.600
Thirty years later, Connie Rice is still trying
to help reform the police.

00:27:00.600 --> 00:27:06.110
She partnered with the LAPD to help create
the Community Safety Partnership, with a holistic

00:27:06.110 --> 00:27:09.809
approach to working in neighborhoods where
mistrust still runs deep.

00:27:09.809 --> 00:27:17.490
CONNIE RICE: The transition has to be from
search and destroy, mass incarceration, shock

00:27:17.490 --> 00:27:23.549
and awe policing, to wraparound safety, heal
and build, guardian policing.

00:27:23.549 --> 00:27:27.540
Gladiator to guardian, that's the culture
change.

00:27:27.540 --> 00:27:33.640
But you can't have that change without all
of the other sectors changing too, civil rights

00:27:33.640 --> 00:27:37.140
lawyers, the residents, government agencies.

00:27:37.140 --> 00:27:38.860
We ask cops to do too much.

00:27:38.860 --> 00:27:44.669
STEPHANIE SY: Rice says she has found like-minded
police chiefs with the same goals, but that

00:27:44.669 --> 00:27:47.669
the message hasn't trickled down to the rank
and file.

00:27:47.669 --> 00:27:54.070
CONNIE RICE: If you stick people in a hellhole,
and you send cops into make sure that what's

00:27:54.070 --> 00:28:00.590
in that ghetto stays there, you're going to
get what we get, which is riots, rebellions,

00:28:00.590 --> 00:28:06.240
uprisings that are triggered by a bad shooting,
a bad stop.

00:28:06.240 --> 00:28:10.679
We're one more video away from that kind of
explosion again.

00:28:10.679 --> 00:28:12.010
STEPHANIE SY: Really?

00:28:12.010 --> 00:28:13.390
You think it is still possible?

00:28:13.390 --> 00:28:19.059
CONNIE RICE: I'm afraid it's going to devolve
again to a level of frustration because there

00:28:19.059 --> 00:28:20.669
isn't enough change.

00:28:20.669 --> 00:28:22.559
The political momentum has slowed.

00:28:22.559 --> 00:28:25.100
The federal legislation stalled.

00:28:25.100 --> 00:28:31.539
So, while you have seen a huge change in the
culture and the Black Lives Matter movement

00:28:31.539 --> 00:28:36.630
has gone global, but it hasn't touched the
DNA of American policing.

00:28:36.630 --> 00:28:41.289
STEPHANIE SY: Have the underlying problems
that existed 30 years ago in South Los Angeles

00:28:41.289 --> 00:28:42.289
been addressed?

00:28:42.289 --> 00:28:48.320
DARNELL HUNT: I mean, all the basic measures
of economic well-being across the different

00:28:48.320 --> 00:28:51.080
racial and ethnic groups, there's been very,
very little progress since 1992.

00:28:51.080 --> 00:28:53.630
And, in some cases, we have gone backwards.

00:28:53.630 --> 00:28:56.330
STEPHANIE SY: So, 1992 really did change your
perspective?

00:28:56.330 --> 00:28:59.450
RHONDA MITCHELL: Oh, 1992 changed everything
for me.

00:28:59.450 --> 00:29:03.010
South L.A. could feel like cocoon, as I went
to the same shops.

00:29:03.010 --> 00:29:05.710
Those shops didn't exist anymore after 1992.

00:29:05.710 --> 00:29:06.710
The world...

00:29:06.710 --> 00:29:07.710
STEPHANIE SY: They were burned down.

00:29:07.710 --> 00:29:08.760
RHONDA MITCHELL: They were burned down.

00:29:08.760 --> 00:29:11.750
The world wasn't like it used to be in 1992.

00:29:11.750 --> 00:29:13.290
It changed.

00:29:13.290 --> 00:29:14.290
It shifted.

00:29:14.290 --> 00:29:18.270
And I have kept -- that shift has stayed with
me since that time, so that's why I wear this

00:29:18.270 --> 00:29:19.270
necklace.

00:29:19.270 --> 00:29:25.110
STEPHANIE SY: In Rhonda's old neighborhood
in South L.A., a new metro line is being built,

00:29:25.110 --> 00:29:31.300
the center of a multimillion-dollar revitalization
project that aims to bring opportunity, while

00:29:31.300 --> 00:29:40.510
celebrating the legacy of Black L.A., a legacy
of creativity, strength, and continuing struggle.

00:29:40.510 --> 00:29:45.929
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm Stephanie Sy in
Los Angeles.

00:29:45.929 --> 00:30:03.279
JUDY WOODRUFF: A new "PBS NewsHour"/NPR/Marist
poll is out today, and it has good news for

00:30:03.279 --> 00:30:08.289
Republicans, but indicates a rocky road ahead
for President Biden and Democrats, as the

00:30:08.289 --> 00:30:10.700
midterm election season swings into gear.

00:30:10.700 --> 00:30:15.570
To help us break it all down, I'm joined by
our political correspondent, Lisa Desjardins.

00:30:15.570 --> 00:30:17.550
Lisa, so, hello.

00:30:17.550 --> 00:30:21.840
First of all, what is in here about how President
Biden is doing?

00:30:21.840 --> 00:30:24.520
LISA DESJARDINS: First of all, I like to tell
people right off the top there is a margin

00:30:24.520 --> 00:30:25.520
of error here.

00:30:25.520 --> 00:30:28.679
It's about 3 or 4 percentage points, depending
on the category.

00:30:28.679 --> 00:30:32.920
Let's look at the president's approval rating
over time, where we are over the past few

00:30:32.920 --> 00:30:33.920
months.

00:30:33.920 --> 00:30:34.920
You see.

00:30:34.920 --> 00:30:35.920
There it was.

00:30:35.920 --> 00:30:37.220
It got lower last -- in March.

00:30:37.220 --> 00:30:39.250
It has increased a little bit, 41 percent.

00:30:39.250 --> 00:30:43.070
But given that margin of error I just talked
about, it's about static.

00:30:43.070 --> 00:30:44.700
It hasn't really changed that much.

00:30:44.700 --> 00:30:50.330
Now, it is technically higher than the approval
rating at the lowest point for President Trump.

00:30:50.330 --> 00:30:53.340
But that's not a comparison that Democrats
want, of course.

00:30:53.340 --> 00:30:56.731
Some good news for Democrats maybe that, at
this point in his term of office, President

00:30:56.731 --> 00:30:59.559
Reagan also had a low approval rating, about
46 percent.

00:30:59.559 --> 00:31:02.740
So this doesn't indicate the fate of a president.

00:31:02.740 --> 00:31:06.659
However, it is a problem for Democrats, of
course, on the ballot in November.

00:31:06.659 --> 00:31:11.290
And I want to drill down into something specific
that may alarm them.

00:31:11.290 --> 00:31:12.809
Let's look at their base a little bit.

00:31:12.809 --> 00:31:18.299
When you asked if people that we have surveyed
if they strongly approve of President Biden,

00:31:18.299 --> 00:31:19.450
let's look at what people said.

00:31:19.450 --> 00:31:20.990
Who strongly approves?

00:31:20.990 --> 00:31:24.990
Only 43 percent of Democrats strongly approve
of the president.

00:31:24.990 --> 00:31:27.029
That's the base that you want to get out.

00:31:27.029 --> 00:31:29.929
Three percent of Republicans, no surprise,
not a lot of strong approval there.

00:31:29.929 --> 00:31:31.419
But look at independents.

00:31:31.419 --> 00:31:35.950
Only 9 percent of independents strongly approve
of President Biden.

00:31:35.950 --> 00:31:40.480
That is a big enthusiasm problem for Democrats
that they have to really think about.

00:31:40.480 --> 00:31:43.420
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, you're talking about Democrats
broadly.

00:31:43.420 --> 00:31:45.809
And you did look more closely at that.

00:31:45.809 --> 00:31:49.730
What does this suggest that Democrats need
to think about for November?

00:31:49.730 --> 00:31:54.570
LISA DESJARDINS: There are some very significant
issues in which Democrats see a larger gap

00:31:54.570 --> 00:31:57.870
forming between them and Democrat -- and Republicans
in public opinion.

00:31:57.870 --> 00:32:00.020
Let's take a look at this by the issues then.

00:32:00.020 --> 00:32:03.560
So the number one issue right now seems to
be the economy, of course.

00:32:03.560 --> 00:32:07.360
So, when you look at the economy there, right
there on the first on the left, the blue line

00:32:07.360 --> 00:32:12.070
indicates people who believe Democrats would
do better with the economy.

00:32:12.070 --> 00:32:16.649
The red line, that much larger line, Republicans,
people who believe Republicans would do better

00:32:16.649 --> 00:32:17.649
with the economy.

00:32:17.649 --> 00:32:22.780
But we also heard from -- we also saw in this
survey that most Americans believe -- more

00:32:22.780 --> 00:32:25.980
Americans, rather, believe that Republicans
would do better on crime.

00:32:25.980 --> 00:32:27.880
Look at that immigration figure.

00:32:27.880 --> 00:32:32.620
By just a narrow amount, more Americans now
believe that Republicans would do a better

00:32:32.620 --> 00:32:35.260
job handling immigration than Democrats.

00:32:35.260 --> 00:32:38.179
That is an issue that Democrats in the past
have done well with.

00:32:38.179 --> 00:32:39.419
Where do Democrats do well?

00:32:39.419 --> 00:32:40.419
Look at that.

00:32:40.419 --> 00:32:44.339
On the coronavirus, more Americans believe
Democrats would do better on that than on

00:32:44.339 --> 00:32:46.340
-- than Republicans do.

00:32:46.340 --> 00:32:48.580
Those are really major issues right now.

00:32:48.580 --> 00:32:49.960
And Democrats are falling behind.

00:32:49.960 --> 00:32:52.429
And the Democrats still do well with things
like climate change.

00:32:52.429 --> 00:32:54.760
They blow Republicans out of the water on
that.

00:32:54.760 --> 00:32:58.480
But talking to our pollster Lee Miringoff
on this, he said it's a real problem, because

00:32:58.480 --> 00:33:01.350
the front-of-mind issues is where Democrats
are losing ground.

00:33:01.350 --> 00:33:03.820
LEE MIRINGOFF, Director, Marist Institute
for Public Opinion: Right now, the issues

00:33:03.820 --> 00:33:09.820
of greatest salience for the voters are the
issues that tend to be favoring the Republicans.

00:33:09.820 --> 00:33:15.250
And that is sort of also driving these general
numbers about why the Republicans are in decent

00:33:15.250 --> 00:33:16.250
shape.

00:33:16.250 --> 00:33:20.080
One big caveat in all that is that we really
don't know right now what's going to be on

00:33:20.080 --> 00:33:22.769
people's minds in October and November.

00:33:22.769 --> 00:33:28.140
What we clearly have learned in the last year
or so is that the issues come and go in very

00:33:28.140 --> 00:33:29.630
fast fashion right now.

00:33:29.630 --> 00:33:33.840
LISA DESJARDINS: One issue he mentioned, abortion
and the Supreme Court decision that we expect

00:33:33.840 --> 00:33:34.840
soon.

00:33:34.840 --> 00:33:38.470
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Lisa, there's another
issue that Republicans have spent a fair amount

00:33:38.470 --> 00:33:40.929
of time emphasizing this year.

00:33:40.929 --> 00:33:42.289
It's education.

00:33:42.289 --> 00:33:44.630
And yet Democrats seem to do well with that.

00:33:44.630 --> 00:33:45.630
LISA DESJARDINS: That's right.

00:33:45.630 --> 00:33:48.929
And there's something really interesting when
you look down at sort of how -- what people

00:33:48.929 --> 00:33:49.929
feel on education.

00:33:49.929 --> 00:33:51.899
Let's take a look at the data that we found.

00:33:51.899 --> 00:33:56.900
You ask all voters who does a better job on
education, overall, more Americans believe

00:33:56.900 --> 00:34:01.049
Democrats, that blue line, 40 percent, would
do better on education.

00:34:01.049 --> 00:34:07.000
But if you ask parents who have children under
the age of 18, people who are in schools,

00:34:07.000 --> 00:34:11.890
in PTAs, they believe Republicans by a narrow
amount would do a better job.

00:34:11.890 --> 00:34:16.099
And that's why you're seeing this problem
at school boards and meetings across the country.

00:34:16.099 --> 00:34:20.879
Those parents are starting to trust Republicans
more than Democrats, though it's close.

00:34:20.879 --> 00:34:21.879
And that is a real issue.

00:34:21.879 --> 00:34:24.540
JUDY WOODRUFF: No doubt or connection to COVID
there.

00:34:24.540 --> 00:34:29.750
And, Lisa, you all -- also looked at some
particular voter groups, including Latinos.

00:34:29.750 --> 00:34:30.750
What did you find?

00:34:30.750 --> 00:34:33.839
LISA DESJARDINS: You know, we have seen in
many cycles that this is a voting group that

00:34:33.839 --> 00:34:36.399
really does -- has not really chosen Republicans,
Democrats.

00:34:36.399 --> 00:34:40.079
And, of course, Latinos aren't monolithic,
many different groups in many different parts

00:34:40.079 --> 00:34:41.079
of the country.

00:34:41.079 --> 00:34:45.369
But I want to look at where Latinos have been
in the past few years in terms of big surveys.

00:34:45.369 --> 00:34:50.560
This is where the percent of Latinos who told
exit holder's in 2020 that they voted for

00:34:50.560 --> 00:34:52.609
President Biden, 65 percent.

00:34:52.609 --> 00:34:53.820
That's a number of Democrats like.

00:34:53.820 --> 00:34:55.409
They would love it to be even higher.

00:34:55.409 --> 00:35:01.800
But, in our survey, this is the percent that
said they would support a Democrat in November,

00:35:01.800 --> 00:35:05.890
39 percent, 52 percent voting Republican.

00:35:05.890 --> 00:35:11.150
And that is a huge issue in some states with
some close elections like Texas and large

00:35:11.150 --> 00:35:13.200
Latino populations.

00:35:13.200 --> 00:35:17.120
It is a population that, when I talk to Latino
leaders on the Hill and otherwise, they feel

00:35:17.120 --> 00:35:19.650
Democrats have not done enough to reach out.

00:35:19.650 --> 00:35:21.320
And perhaps that's what we're seeing in this
poll.

00:35:21.320 --> 00:35:25.460
JUDY WOODRUFF: It would be really interesting
to understand what issues matter most to Latino

00:35:25.460 --> 00:35:26.460
voters.

00:35:26.460 --> 00:35:27.460
LISA DESJARDINS: Yes.

00:35:27.460 --> 00:35:28.460
We will have more polls ahead.

00:35:28.460 --> 00:35:30.220
JUDY WOODRUFF: Lisa Desjardins thank you.

00:35:30.220 --> 00:35:38.500
LISA DESJARDINS: You're welcome.

00:35:38.500 --> 00:35:48.130
JUDY WOODRUFF: As you just heard, our "PBS
NewsHour"/NPR/Marist poll gives us some insights

00:35:48.130 --> 00:35:50.450
into what voters are thinking right now.

00:35:50.450 --> 00:35:56.660
Plus, the president has asked Congress for
a big increase in assistance to Ukraine.

00:35:56.660 --> 00:36:02.900
And the GOP is brushing aside audiotapes that
captured party leaders criticizing their own.

00:36:02.900 --> 00:36:06.760
We turn now to the analysis of Brooks and
Capehart.

00:36:06.760 --> 00:36:11.980
That's New York Times columnist David Brooks,
and Jonathan Capehart, associate editor for

00:36:11.980 --> 00:36:13.080
The Washington Post.

00:36:13.080 --> 00:36:17.240
And it is great to see the two of you on this
Friday night.

00:36:17.240 --> 00:36:18.940
Thank you for being here.

00:36:18.940 --> 00:36:24.320
Let's just pick up right now, David, with
that poll, really interesting analysis by

00:36:24.320 --> 00:36:25.350
Lisa.

00:36:25.350 --> 00:36:26.460
What did you see there?

00:36:26.460 --> 00:36:28.540
What stood out to you?

00:36:28.540 --> 00:36:34.300
DAVID BROOKS: The two things Lisa mentioned
really leapt out of me, first, the Latino

00:36:34.300 --> 00:36:39.930
vote, 52 percent favoring Republicans, 55
percent Latino disapproval of Joe Biden.

00:36:39.930 --> 00:36:43.290
These are -- this should be four alarm bells
for Democrats.

00:36:43.290 --> 00:36:45.890
Latinos have been -- have not been shifting
over to the Republicans.

00:36:45.890 --> 00:36:49.530
They have done -- Donald Trump had done reasonably
well with Latinos.

00:36:49.530 --> 00:36:52.830
But the Latino still identify overwhelmingly
with Democrats.

00:36:52.830 --> 00:36:56.180
But they're clearly not happy with the way
things are going.

00:36:56.180 --> 00:36:58.200
And then the second issue is education.

00:36:58.200 --> 00:37:02.920
If you go back -- Pew Research Center does
these polls constantly, which party do you

00:37:02.920 --> 00:37:05.220
trust more on education?

00:37:05.220 --> 00:37:09.620
And if you go back over the decades, Democrats
usually have a 20-point advantage, a 26-point

00:37:09.620 --> 00:37:11.720
advantage, something pretty big.

00:37:11.720 --> 00:37:16.540
And that's down to 20 -- or that's now down
to basically zero.

00:37:16.540 --> 00:37:20.650
And so I think that's partly the schools closing
at the teachers union behest.

00:37:20.650 --> 00:37:25.310
It's partly some efforts to get rid of the
magnet schools and gifted programs.

00:37:25.310 --> 00:37:29.250
And I think it's partly a sense that too many
progressives are trying to do everything with

00:37:29.250 --> 00:37:30.400
education in the schools.

00:37:30.400 --> 00:37:35.119
But, clearly, on those issues, it's helping
Republicans, especially those with kids.

00:37:35.119 --> 00:37:38.220
And so this is, across the board, pretty grim
for Democrats.

00:37:38.220 --> 00:37:41.840
JUDY WOODRUFF: How do you look at these numbers,
Jonathan?

00:37:41.840 --> 00:37:42.840
(LAUGHTER)

00:37:42.840 --> 00:37:45.599
JONATHAN CAPEHART: So, David was paying attention
to the Latino numbers.

00:37:45.599 --> 00:37:52.100
I went to the African American numbers, because
the African American vote is the base of the

00:37:52.100 --> 00:37:53.150
Democratic Party.

00:37:53.150 --> 00:37:55.490
It is the base of President Biden.

00:37:55.490 --> 00:37:56.990
That's why he's president.

00:37:56.990 --> 00:38:02.610
And yet his standing among Black voters, his
approval rating is 64 percent.

00:38:02.610 --> 00:38:07.630
That should raise alarm bells in the White
House, if it hasn't already.

00:38:07.630 --> 00:38:14.030
I think it's because of no movement on voting
rights, no movement on criminal justice reform.

00:38:14.030 --> 00:38:15.270
We will see what happens.

00:38:15.270 --> 00:38:20.180
As Lee Miringoff said, who knows what people
will care about in October, but I bet -- maybe

00:38:20.180 --> 00:38:25.550
the president will get a bump up when Justice
Ketanji Brown Jackson officially takes the

00:38:25.550 --> 00:38:28.430
oath of office to be the next justice in the
Supreme Court.

00:38:28.430 --> 00:38:34.130
And, then to mimic David, there's a second
thing that leapt out at me, the inflation

00:38:34.130 --> 00:38:40.080
numbers, the crime numbers, and the national
security numbers all not in the Democratic

00:38:40.080 --> 00:38:41.490
Party's favor.

00:38:41.490 --> 00:38:46.859
Those, particularly inflation and crime, are
-- quote, unquote -- "emotional issues."

00:38:46.859 --> 00:38:48.660
People -- people go to the ballot box....

00:38:48.660 --> 00:38:49.660
JUDY WOODRUFF: Your earpiece...

00:38:49.660 --> 00:38:50.660
(LAUGHTER)

00:38:50.660 --> 00:38:53.950
JONATHAN CAPEHART: My earpiece just fell out,
everyone.

00:38:53.950 --> 00:38:58.070
But if the administration can't talk to the
American people convincingly that they have

00:38:58.070 --> 00:39:02.089
crime under control and inflation under control,
they will be in trouble.

00:39:02.089 --> 00:39:06.260
JUDY WOODRUFF: David, are these the kinds
of things that Democrats have the ability

00:39:06.260 --> 00:39:13.570
over the next six, seven, eight months to
change voters' thinking, or are these issues

00:39:13.570 --> 00:39:17.000
that are essentially just entrenched right
now?

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:21.230
DAVID BROOKS: Not entrenched, but super hard
to change this around.

00:39:21.230 --> 00:39:25.590
Basically, the whole zeitgeist of the country
has deteriorated over the last year.

00:39:25.590 --> 00:39:30.550
And I would say it's been a threat of disorder,
disorder on many fronts, disorder internationally

00:39:30.550 --> 00:39:33.240
with Ukraine, disorder at home, crime.

00:39:33.240 --> 00:39:39.619
Crime in New York is surging by 30 percent
year over year, 30, 40 in some -- robbery

00:39:39.619 --> 00:39:43.060
and burglary up to 40 or 50 percent.

00:39:43.060 --> 00:39:45.270
Inflation is a form of economic disorder.

00:39:45.270 --> 00:39:50.770
And so people just feel that the world has
become less safe on a whole variety of fronts.

00:39:50.770 --> 00:39:55.480
And, traditionally, Republicans have been
the party of order, and Democrats have been

00:39:55.480 --> 00:39:58.130
the party of fairness and justice.

00:39:58.130 --> 00:40:04.470
And so there has been historically an attempt
to turn to Republicans when you feel unsafe.

00:40:04.470 --> 00:40:06.440
And so Democrats have to turn that around.

00:40:06.440 --> 00:40:08.020
Now, they have turned it around in the past.

00:40:08.020 --> 00:40:12.690
In the 1990s, Tony Blair and Bill Clinton
-- Tony Blair had a phrase tough on crime

00:40:12.690 --> 00:40:14.260
and tough on the causes of crime.

00:40:14.260 --> 00:40:19.990
And that was an attempt to create an anti-crime
strategy, say, for those in the center-left.

00:40:19.990 --> 00:40:21.369
And so it can be done.

00:40:21.369 --> 00:40:22.369
But it's a heavy lift.

00:40:22.369 --> 00:40:24.870
And it takes a lot of time and a lot of persuasion.

00:40:24.870 --> 00:40:26.579
I'm not sure there's enough time to do it
before the midterms.

00:40:26.579 --> 00:40:27.880
JUDY WOODRUFF: What do you see here?

00:40:27.880 --> 00:40:31.800
Do you see there's a chance on any -- well,
you -- and you were talking about among Black

00:40:31.800 --> 00:40:32.800
voters.

00:40:32.800 --> 00:40:34.840
But where's the opportunity for Democrats
here?

00:40:34.840 --> 00:40:39.920
JONATHAN CAPEHART: Well, I think the opportunity
comes in another set of numbers that I looked

00:40:39.920 --> 00:40:43.980
at, and the poll points out Trump's approval
rating.

00:40:43.980 --> 00:40:47.230
And Donald Trump's approval rating is at 39
percent.

00:40:47.230 --> 00:40:53.569
His disapproval is at 56 percent, not unsimilar,
dissimilar to President Biden's.

00:40:53.569 --> 00:40:59.099
But if you are a Democrat running against
candidates that have been endorsed by Donald

00:40:59.099 --> 00:41:03.810
Trump or who haven't run away from Donald
Trump, that gives you something to run on,

00:41:03.810 --> 00:41:08.670
because, in the end, those candidates only
have their fealty to Trump to run on, whereas

00:41:08.670 --> 00:41:13.720
the Democrats have something to actually talk
about, about what they want to do, real plans.

00:41:13.720 --> 00:41:14.720
JUDY WOODRUFF: Right.

00:41:14.720 --> 00:41:15.720
You -- and you mentioned...

00:41:15.720 --> 00:41:16.720
(CROSSTALK)

00:41:16.720 --> 00:41:17.920
DAVID BROOKS: Can I disagree with Jonathan
just on...

00:41:17.920 --> 00:41:18.920
(CROSSTALK)

00:41:18.920 --> 00:41:19.920
(LAUGHTER)

00:41:19.920 --> 00:41:20.920
JUDY WOODRUFF: Sure.

00:41:20.920 --> 00:41:21.920
Sure.

00:41:21.920 --> 00:41:23.520
DAVID BROOKS: Because I think running against
Donald Trump is a gigantic mistake.

00:41:23.520 --> 00:41:27.099
I think that's what we saw in the Glenn Youngkin-Terry
McAuliffe race in Virginia.

00:41:27.099 --> 00:41:31.100
I think people are really -- are really struggling
with issues right in front of their face,

00:41:31.100 --> 00:41:37.170
the gas prices, and things that are incredibly
close to home.

00:41:37.170 --> 00:41:40.120
And I just don't think there's been that much
evidence that running against Donald Trump

00:41:40.120 --> 00:41:43.460
is super effective at getting those voters
who are willing to swing back and forth.

00:41:43.460 --> 00:41:46.250
JONATHAN CAPEHART: But that's what I -- but
that's what I was talking about -- talking

00:41:46.250 --> 00:41:51.560
about, David, that if a Democrat is running
against a Trumper, that Democrat will be able

00:41:51.560 --> 00:41:55.160
to talk about those issues that you're talking
about, what they want to do about inflation,

00:41:55.160 --> 00:41:59.329
what they want to do about jobs, what they
want to do about crime, whereas the other

00:41:59.329 --> 00:42:03.319
candidate might be talking about all sorts
of other things that those voters don't care

00:42:03.319 --> 00:42:04.319
about.

00:42:04.319 --> 00:42:05.620
JUDY WOODRUFF: OK.

00:42:05.620 --> 00:42:06.780
All right.

00:42:06.780 --> 00:42:07.780
(LAUGHTER)

00:42:07.780 --> 00:42:09.770
JUDY WOODRUFF: We move it to...

00:42:09.770 --> 00:42:11.430
DAVID BROOKS: We have achieved clarity.

00:42:11.430 --> 00:42:12.430
(LAUGHTER)

00:42:12.430 --> 00:42:13.430
JUDY WOODRUFF: But one -- it was interesting.

00:42:13.430 --> 00:42:14.520
One of you mentioned national security.

00:42:14.520 --> 00:42:19.470
And, David, I want to come back to you on
this, because, at this point, on Ukraine,

00:42:19.470 --> 00:42:26.690
which is in the news every single night -- we're
watching that terrible war grind on -- the

00:42:26.690 --> 00:42:31.080
Republicans do seem to be, in January -- yes,
they say President Biden should have moved

00:42:31.080 --> 00:42:38.200
sooner, but they do seem to be on board with
approving the money, additional aid, military,

00:42:38.200 --> 00:42:42.400
economic and humanitarian, he's asking for
Ukraine.

00:42:42.400 --> 00:42:45.440
But we don't see any of that working to the
president's benefit.

00:42:45.440 --> 00:42:47.460
Is that -- is that how you see it?

00:42:47.460 --> 00:42:52.680
DAVID BROOKS: It's really stunning to me that
if you get a 49 disapproval on a bipartisan

00:42:52.680 --> 00:42:54.030
policy that's extremely popular.

00:42:54.030 --> 00:42:55.030
JUDY WOODRUFF: Yes.

00:42:55.030 --> 00:42:57.359
DAVID BROOKS: And it just shows the bad mood
the country is in.

00:42:57.359 --> 00:43:01.290
And so, this week, the president -- I think
we -- it's grim news for the president, but

00:43:01.290 --> 00:43:04.920
he's done a fantastic job, especially this
week, on Ukraine.

00:43:04.920 --> 00:43:07.829
This aid package that he outlined is super
aggressive.

00:43:07.829 --> 00:43:08.829
It's big.

00:43:08.829 --> 00:43:10.210
And it's what Ukraine needs.

00:43:10.210 --> 00:43:12.720
The war is changing as it moves to the east.

00:43:12.720 --> 00:43:15.880
There's less sort of maneuverability for the
Ukrainian.

00:43:15.880 --> 00:43:19.730
And so that's much more wide open spaces,
and the Russian tanks are going to be more

00:43:19.730 --> 00:43:20.730
effective.

00:43:20.730 --> 00:43:21.730
They're closer to their supply lines.

00:43:21.730 --> 00:43:26.020
And so Ukraine just needs a lot more heavy
equipment, including tanks and things like

00:43:26.020 --> 00:43:27.020
that.

00:43:27.020 --> 00:43:31.290
And Biden has risen -- with some long-range
artillery and things like, the Biden administration

00:43:31.290 --> 00:43:33.330
has really risen to the occasion.

00:43:33.330 --> 00:43:36.670
And so I would say to him, this is not a moment
to think about how this is polling.

00:43:36.670 --> 00:43:38.520
This is a moment to do what's right for the
world.

00:43:38.520 --> 00:43:40.290
And, as far as I can tell, he's doing that.

00:43:40.290 --> 00:43:44.810
JUDY WOODRUFF: How do you see this aid package
and what the prospects are for getting bipartisan

00:43:44.810 --> 00:43:45.859
support for it?

00:43:45.859 --> 00:43:50.490
JONATHAN CAPEHART: Well, I mean, I agree 100
percent with David in his assessment of the

00:43:50.490 --> 00:43:51.810
president's leadership here.

00:43:51.810 --> 00:43:59.550
And I also think that Congress will remain
on board and will pass these budget requests

00:43:59.550 --> 00:44:00.820
from the president.

00:44:00.820 --> 00:44:06.490
The question I have, and I know the question
that is being pondered in the White House,

00:44:06.490 --> 00:44:08.750
is, how long is this going to last?

00:44:08.750 --> 00:44:15.000
What is the appetite of the American people
to see, every couple of weeks, multibillion-dollar

00:44:15.000 --> 00:44:23.270
packages going -- going overseas, when there
are domestic issues and domestic priorities

00:44:23.270 --> 00:44:29.180
that aren't being addressed so quickly, i.e,
say, lots of people care about student debt?

00:44:29.180 --> 00:44:32.260
Lots of people want to know, where's the child
tax credit?

00:44:32.260 --> 00:44:34.800
There are lots of things that could be -- that
could be funded.

00:44:34.800 --> 00:44:40.150
But the president has made it very clear,
the administration has made it very clear

00:44:40.150 --> 00:44:45.829
that the war -- Russia's war on Ukraine isn't
just an invasion of one country of over another.

00:44:45.829 --> 00:44:48.160
It is democracy vs. autocracy.

00:44:48.160 --> 00:44:50.720
And that is -- and that is what's guiding
the president.

00:44:50.720 --> 00:44:51.720
And I agree with David.

00:44:51.720 --> 00:44:56.050
The president doesn't care about his legacy,
about how this polls.

00:44:56.050 --> 00:45:00.619
This is an existential threat that's taking
place on the European continent.

00:45:00.619 --> 00:45:03.290
JUDY WOODRUFF: And it is interesting, as we
said, that he doesn't seem to be getting any

00:45:03.290 --> 00:45:05.220
credit from the public for what he's doing.

00:45:05.220 --> 00:45:06.220
JONATHAN CAPEHART: Right, not right now.

00:45:06.220 --> 00:45:08.880
JUDY WOODRUFF: David -- excuse me -- I do
want to come back to this question of aid

00:45:08.880 --> 00:45:09.880
for Ukraine.

00:45:09.880 --> 00:45:13.540
I mean, to Jonathan's point, it's, what, $33
billion this time.

00:45:13.540 --> 00:45:17.310
It was several billion the month before that
and the month before that.

00:45:17.310 --> 00:45:19.710
This war looks like it's going to go on for
a long time.

00:45:19.710 --> 00:45:25.880
Is there a limit to what Americans are going
to be prepared to do for Ukraine?

00:45:25.880 --> 00:45:29.670
DAVID BROOKS: So far, we haven't seen any
evidence of it.

00:45:29.670 --> 00:45:31.930
If anything, the taste for action seems to
be growing.

00:45:31.930 --> 00:45:36.500
I mean, if you look over at Europe, they're
really willing to cut off energy supplies

00:45:36.500 --> 00:45:37.500
from Russia.

00:45:37.500 --> 00:45:39.349
That, I would never have expected.

00:45:39.349 --> 00:45:44.880
And so, if there's any momentum here in the
Western alliance's willingness to sacrifice

00:45:44.880 --> 00:45:47.980
for this, it seems to be increasing, not decreasing.

00:45:47.980 --> 00:45:51.690
And one thing COVID did, we got used to $1.9
trillion bills.

00:45:51.690 --> 00:45:52.690
(LAUGHTER)

00:45:52.690 --> 00:45:54.870
DAVID BROOKS: So, a $35 billion bill doesn't
seem that big anymore.

00:45:54.870 --> 00:45:55.870
(LAUGHTER)

00:45:55.870 --> 00:45:59.240
JUDY WOODRUFF: You are right, putting it in
perspective.

00:45:59.240 --> 00:46:04.260
But just in the last few minutes we have,
I want to come back, Jonathan, to something

00:46:04.260 --> 00:46:08.970
that it first surfaced last week, but, this
week, more audiotapes from the House Republican

00:46:08.970 --> 00:46:10.800
leader, Kevin McCarthy.

00:46:10.800 --> 00:46:16.000
And the ones that emerged this week have him
expressing real concern about some of the

00:46:16.000 --> 00:46:22.280
far right members of the House Republican
Caucus, and the effect that they -- that what

00:46:22.280 --> 00:46:28.680
they were saying and doing could lead to even
terrible things happening.

00:46:28.680 --> 00:46:30.880
This was after January the 6th.

00:46:30.880 --> 00:46:32.940
Here we are all these months later.

00:46:32.940 --> 00:46:34.810
Kevin McCarthy brushes it off.

00:46:34.810 --> 00:46:36.060
Do we just forget it?

00:46:36.060 --> 00:46:38.319
I mean, is it -- what does it all add up to?

00:46:38.319 --> 00:46:41.180
JONATHAN CAPEHART: Well, look, we can't forget
it.

00:46:41.180 --> 00:46:48.420
We need to listen to Kevin McCarthy in real
time being a true leader, expressing the horror

00:46:48.420 --> 00:46:52.330
over what happened, the danger that it posed
to the country.

00:46:52.330 --> 00:46:58.180
And then contrast that to where he is today,
which is the complete opposite.

00:46:58.180 --> 00:47:03.560
And what it says to me is that the Republican
Party, the Republican Caucus in the House,

00:47:03.560 --> 00:47:08.849
and the House minority leader are willing
to lie about what they have -- what they have

00:47:08.849 --> 00:47:13.930
done and what they have said, all for the
purpose of winning back the majority in the

00:47:13.930 --> 00:47:14.930
midterms.

00:47:14.930 --> 00:47:19.480
And that leads to an even bigger question
for me, which is, if the House minority leader

00:47:19.480 --> 00:47:25.450
is willing to lie, when we can read the words
and hear the words with our own ears, then

00:47:25.450 --> 00:47:27.920
what does a Speaker McCarthy do?

00:47:27.920 --> 00:47:30.079
How can the American people trust what he
says?

00:47:30.079 --> 00:47:35.240
How can the American press that has to cover
him, how do we trust what he says?

00:47:35.240 --> 00:47:38.470
That is the bigger problem for the Republican
Party.

00:47:38.470 --> 00:47:40.880
But then it could also be a bigger problem
for the country.

00:47:40.880 --> 00:47:44.050
JUDY WOODRUFF: How do you answer some of those
questions, David?

00:47:44.050 --> 00:47:47.680
DAVID BROOKS: Well, first, when I started
doing this job, and I would interview people,

00:47:47.680 --> 00:47:51.430
and people would flat-out lie to me, or even
lie about interviews I had done, I was sort

00:47:51.430 --> 00:47:52.430
of shocked.

00:47:52.430 --> 00:47:54.490
And now I'm a little more used to it.

00:47:54.490 --> 00:47:56.319
It's something that gets done here.

00:47:56.319 --> 00:47:57.930
There is lying in Washington.

00:47:57.930 --> 00:47:59.859
Kevin McCarthy is a nice guy, an affable guy.

00:47:59.859 --> 00:48:01.960
He doesn't particularly have convictions.

00:48:01.960 --> 00:48:03.450
And so he just has blown with the wind.

00:48:03.450 --> 00:48:05.369
And that, he's been consistent upon.

00:48:05.369 --> 00:48:08.490
I think what's interesting is, is there a
scandal?

00:48:08.490 --> 00:48:11.040
It's only a scandal if Donald Trump says it's
a scandal.

00:48:11.040 --> 00:48:14.349
And Donald Trump has decided, intelligently,
it's not a scandal.

00:48:14.349 --> 00:48:16.510
It shows how much power he has.

00:48:16.510 --> 00:48:20.599
And he has basically -- and he now holds -- he
now owns Kevin McCarthy, because he's got

00:48:20.599 --> 00:48:21.760
something on him.

00:48:21.760 --> 00:48:25.420
And so this has been a very good maneuver
for Donald Trump.

00:48:25.420 --> 00:48:29.550
JUDY WOODRUFF: With that, we're going to thank
the both of you.

00:48:29.550 --> 00:48:33.140
David Brooks, Jonathan Capehart, thank you.

00:48:33.140 --> 00:48:39.910
JONATHAN CAPEHART: Thanks, Judy.

00:48:39.910 --> 00:48:49.580
JUDY WOODRUFF: A new novel imagines a world
in which our memories can be accessed and

00:48:49.580 --> 00:48:53.420
reviewed by ourselves and by others.

00:48:53.420 --> 00:48:58.630
Jeffrey Brown talks to Pulitzer Prize-winning
author Jennifer Egan at her home in Brooklyn

00:48:58.630 --> 00:49:00.910
about her latest work of fiction.

00:49:00.910 --> 00:49:04.210
It's part of our arts and culture series,
Canvas.

00:49:04.210 --> 00:49:10.760
JEFFREY BROWN: Imagine a beautiful cube in
which you can store all your memories, allowing

00:49:10.760 --> 00:49:13.030
access to them whenever you want.

00:49:13.030 --> 00:49:15.609
Call it own your unconscious.

00:49:15.609 --> 00:49:17.480
But there is a tradeoff.

00:49:17.480 --> 00:49:22.290
Others can access it, or, in a sense, you.

00:49:22.290 --> 00:49:27.490
Novelist Jennifer Egan has dreamed up this
so far nonexistent technology.

00:49:27.490 --> 00:49:31.059
She may still write by hand in the office
of her Brooklyn home.

00:49:31.059 --> 00:49:35.770
but, like most of us, she finds much of her
own life bound up in the digital world.

00:49:35.770 --> 00:49:38.579
JENNIFER EGAN, Author, "The Candy House":
I feel like that's the great story I have

00:49:38.579 --> 00:49:39.819
witnessed in my lifetime.

00:49:39.819 --> 00:49:48.230
You know, the speed of change in the telecommunication
realm, the media realm is so fast that I feel

00:49:48.230 --> 00:49:53.160
like I continually revisit the question of
how that affects us internally.

00:49:53.160 --> 00:49:56.119
JEFFREY BROWN: And why does that interest
you as a novelist?

00:49:56.119 --> 00:50:01.400
JENNIFER EGAN: Because the novel is the instrument
to examine inside people's minds.

00:50:01.400 --> 00:50:06.410
I mean, that's -- as far as I can see, that's
the unique thing that novels do that nothing

00:50:06.410 --> 00:50:07.410
else can do.

00:50:07.410 --> 00:50:12.190
JEFFREY BROWN: Egan's new novel, "The Candy
House," looks into her characters' minds and

00:50:12.190 --> 00:50:17.859
also plays with literary forms, something
she has done in six previous works, each different

00:50:17.859 --> 00:50:18.859
from the last.

00:50:18.859 --> 00:50:24.840
The new one draws on characters and storylines
from her 2010 Pulitzer Prize-winning "A Visit

00:50:24.840 --> 00:50:25.890
from the Goon Squad."

00:50:25.890 --> 00:50:32.480
And each chapter is written in a different
voice or perspective and uses different styles,

00:50:32.480 --> 00:50:35.980
including an e-mail exchange and a futuristic
spy story.

00:50:35.980 --> 00:50:40.690
JENNIFER EGAN: In a way, what the book does
is simulate this experience of being in a

00:50:40.690 --> 00:50:44.570
collective consciousness and moving in and
out of world's and people's minds.

00:50:44.570 --> 00:50:45.570
Imagine...

00:50:45.570 --> 00:50:46.810
JEFFREY BROWN: A fragmented world, yes.

00:50:46.810 --> 00:50:51.750
JENNIFER EGAN: Right, or a fragmented experience,
which is very much what online experience

00:50:51.750 --> 00:50:53.470
often is.

00:50:53.470 --> 00:50:57.290
Imagine trying to tell that story conventionally.

00:50:57.290 --> 00:50:59.390
My last novel was a historical novel.

00:50:59.390 --> 00:51:01.740
I told it in a very straightforward way.

00:51:01.740 --> 00:51:04.750
It couldn't have lived in a form like this.

00:51:04.750 --> 00:51:10.950
But one way to keep things fresh and to keep
myself doing things I haven't done before

00:51:10.950 --> 00:51:17.349
is to try to use new ways of doing them, because
that will require that I tell a story I have

00:51:17.349 --> 00:51:18.630
never told.

00:51:18.630 --> 00:51:20.059
I just love being near the water.

00:51:20.059 --> 00:51:24.030
JEFFREY BROWN: On one of her favorite walks
along the East River, she said that, while

00:51:24.030 --> 00:51:29.700
ideas get her going, it's the characters who
take over, beginning in this case with Bix,

00:51:29.700 --> 00:51:35.280
a world-famous social media entrepreneur,
dreaming up the next big thing.

00:51:35.280 --> 00:51:40.770
Chapter by chapter, we meet others embracing
or alienated by this new world.

00:51:40.770 --> 00:51:41.770
Are you a techie yourself?

00:51:41.770 --> 00:51:42.770
I mean, is this your world?

00:51:42.770 --> 00:51:43.770
JENNIFER EGAN: No.

00:51:43.770 --> 00:51:44.770
(LAUGHTER)

00:51:44.770 --> 00:51:45.770
JEFFREY BROWN: No?

00:51:45.770 --> 00:51:47.680
JENNIFER EGAN: I'm a late and incompetent
adopter.

00:51:47.680 --> 00:51:48.680
(LAUGHTER)

00:51:48.680 --> 00:51:49.680
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

00:51:49.680 --> 00:51:50.680
JENNIFER EGAN: I'm...

00:51:50.680 --> 00:51:51.940
JEFFREY BROWN: But, somehow, that made you
want to explore it in a way?

00:51:51.940 --> 00:51:55.910
JENNIFER EGAN: Well, I'm interested in it
because it interests other people.

00:51:55.910 --> 00:52:02.640
You know, anything that impacts the way people
live and think is so fascinating to me, and

00:52:02.640 --> 00:52:05.620
especially something new, because I'm interested
in change.

00:52:05.620 --> 00:52:09.829
I mean, in a way, that's what fiction is all
about, sort of watching things change over

00:52:09.829 --> 00:52:11.450
some unit of time.

00:52:11.450 --> 00:52:16.290
JEFFREY BROWN: George Orwell's "1984," she
thinks, got it half right.

00:52:16.290 --> 00:52:20.890
Screens are everywhere in our lives, but we
invite them in.

00:52:20.890 --> 00:52:25.120
Are you afraid that we're losing our sense
of privacy and our sense of authenticity?

00:52:25.120 --> 00:52:29.579
JENNIFER EGAN: You know, I have various thoughts
about it as a civilian.

00:52:29.579 --> 00:52:34.230
But what I feel, as a fiction writer, is just
total curiosity.

00:52:34.230 --> 00:52:37.490
I don't know what -- really what the implications
of all of this are.

00:52:37.490 --> 00:52:43.359
And I think any thought I have has to be put
in the context of my age and my generation.

00:52:43.359 --> 00:52:49.430
My children will tell you I'm anti-screen
and deprive them of important cultural experiences

00:52:49.430 --> 00:52:51.530
by not letting them play enough video games.

00:52:51.530 --> 00:52:52.530
(LAUGHTER)

00:52:52.530 --> 00:52:54.640
JENNIFER EGAN: But the truth is, I don't know.

00:52:54.640 --> 00:53:02.849
I feel a kind of dread as a human that I hope
doesn't seep too much into my fiction, because,

00:53:02.849 --> 00:53:03.980
in a way, it's inappropriate.

00:53:03.980 --> 00:53:11.210
And, as a fiction writer, my job is to transcend
that and just enter the realm of human experience

00:53:11.210 --> 00:53:13.069
without judgments.

00:53:13.069 --> 00:53:20.050
For me, fiction is where I ask questions and
where I go to ask questions as a reader.

00:53:20.050 --> 00:53:23.880
JEFFREY BROWN: I can't help think that all
these things we're talking about, the themes

00:53:23.880 --> 00:53:29.290
you're addressing, the experimentation with
form, they're all kind of tied to larger questions

00:53:29.290 --> 00:53:31.420
of literary fiction today.

00:53:31.420 --> 00:53:34.160
Like, what's it for, right?

00:53:34.160 --> 00:53:35.869
How relevant is it?

00:53:35.869 --> 00:53:36.869
Who's it for?

00:53:36.869 --> 00:53:41.930
JENNIFER EGAN: To me, the reason fiction still
exists is that it is still relevant, because

00:53:41.930 --> 00:53:47.839
we do have a curiosity to be inside the minds
of other people, one of the things that we

00:53:47.839 --> 00:53:50.440
can never actually do in real life.

00:53:50.440 --> 00:53:51.440
It won't happen.

00:53:51.440 --> 00:53:52.440
JEFFREY BROWN: So far.

00:53:52.440 --> 00:53:53.440
(LAUGHTER)

00:53:53.440 --> 00:53:54.440
JENNIFER EGAN: Because I made up the machine.

00:53:54.440 --> 00:53:55.440
(LAUGHTER)

00:53:55.440 --> 00:53:57.960
JENNIFER EGAN: We don't understand the brain
well enough to actually do it.

00:53:57.960 --> 00:54:04.430
But there is one slight problem, which is
that we are so image-fixated as a culture

00:54:04.430 --> 00:54:08.670
now, and the screens reinforce that every
moment.

00:54:08.670 --> 00:54:16.420
And we are so used to skidding around and
not focusing that long on any one thing, that

00:54:16.420 --> 00:54:23.430
the muscles that are required to actually
read a book can feel a little flabby.

00:54:23.430 --> 00:54:29.480
I just want to keep people -- keep people's
imaginations strong and nimble enough to have

00:54:29.480 --> 00:54:30.490
those experiences.

00:54:30.490 --> 00:54:34.940
JEFFREY BROWN: So you're worried a bit, but
you're a true believer in fiction's power.

00:54:34.940 --> 00:54:40.839
JENNIFER EGAN: I'm a true believer in fiction's
ability to offer something in the form of

00:54:40.839 --> 00:54:43.860
entertainment that nothing else is quite doing.

00:54:43.860 --> 00:54:46.710
So, yes, I think it is still relevant.

00:54:46.710 --> 00:54:48.660
And I hope people will keep reading it.

00:54:48.660 --> 00:54:51.200
JEFFREY BROWN: All right, the book is "The
Candy House."

00:54:51.200 --> 00:54:52.960
Jennifer Egan, thank you very much.

00:54:52.960 --> 00:54:54.119
JENNIFER EGAN: Thank you.

00:54:54.119 --> 00:54:57.339
JUDY WOODRUFF: Got to keep up those reading
muscles.

00:54:57.339 --> 00:54:59.339
And that is the "NewsHour" for tonight.

00:54:59.339 --> 00:55:00.339
I'm Judy Woodruff.

00:55:00.339 --> 00:56:43.790
Please stay safe, and we will see you soon.

